VERDICT: confirmed-but-no-uca
UCA: N/A
REASON: The finding is real. In src/device_init.rs, init_device (lines 228-280) unconditionally sets dev.initialized = true at line 270 before branching on `success`, leaving a failed device in the state (initialized=true, init_res=1). check_deps_satisfied (lines 317-344) only inspects devices[dep_id].initialized at line 334 and ignores init_res, while is_ready_spec (lines 158-160) and is_device_ready (line 349) correctly require both. Tracing the finding's PoC against the source confirms: after init_device(dep, success=false), is_device_ready(dep) = false yet check_deps_satisfied(dependent, [dep, dependent]) = true, so a dependent passes the DI4 gate against a broken predecessor. This contradicts SWREQ-DI-DI04 (artifacts/requirements.yaml:4459-4474), which explicitly requires "successfully initialized" dependencies and names check_deps_satisfied() as its verification criterion — the Verus ensures clause that would catch this is missing. The scenario needs no unusual hardware, no SMP ordering, no precondition violation; any driver returning non-zero triggers it. Mapping to UCA: artifacts/stpa.yaml explicitly states "Control structure, UCAs, and loss scenarios are out of scope for this initial artifact" (lines 11-13) and contains only L-*, H-*, SC-* entries; no safety/stpa/ucas.yaml file exists in the repository. No existing UCA can be selected. A new UCA is needed along the lines of: "Device init controller marks a device ready / advances dependents even though the device's init function returned failure," linking hazard H-2-like class (silent data integrity loss during boot) to L-2 via system constraint SWREQ-DI-DI04.
